paragraphs.text:
%md #Graph Algorithm to-date in SciSpark Purpose: This notebook will demonstrate using SciSpark to: * read in netCDF files * mask areas in an array meeting a criteria * connect these areas via overlap between two time steps to form a graph object. * This graph is searched to find subgraphs meeting a minimum length criteria, and are visualized. These are all the steps conducted to identify and track mesoscale convective systems (MCSs). For this demonstration, hrly data for 1st August 2006 of the brightness temperature NCEP/CPC MERG dataset over location 5S - 40N, 60E - 90W is used. More information about the NCEP/CPC 4km MERG Dataset used for this demonstration can be found [here] (http://mirador.gsfc.nasa.gov/collections/MERG__001.shtml).
The algorithm for this implementation is given below. ![Distributed GTG in MR Paradigm](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SciSpark/scispark_zeppelin_notebooks/master/images/GTGMR.png) Figure 1: The distributed GTG in MR Paradigm This notebook environment contains all the classes and dependencies necessary to use SciSpark.By default we have loaded the SciSpark jar into the Zeppelin and Spark environment in the config folder. Note that in the nomenclature used in this notebook, a *frame* indicates the date and time associated with a netCDF file.

paragraphs.text:
%md
##Connect the cloud elements between frames
In order to observe features are forming over time, it is necessary to connect *cloud elements* between *frames*. The connection, referred to as an *edge*, is created between *cloud elements* of consecutive *frames* if: 
* the area between consecutive frames is >= 2400.00 squared_km
OR
* the area between consecutive frames is < 2400.00 squared_km and the convective fraction is < 0.9. The convective fraction is defined as the ratio of minimum to maximum brightness temperature

At the end of this step, a sparely connected graph representing the  cloud elements found and their connectivity through out the user defined datasets. 

Notice the **sciTensor** is being passed around and manipulated.

paragraphs.text:
%md 
## Find the subgraphs
These subgraphs physically identify the cloudy areas that have evolve in time
Right now we are reading the edgeList from a file which has to send to HDFS 
There is a bit of cleaning of the file to be done before moving to HDFS. More specifically, remove 'List(' from the beginning of the file and last ')' at the end of the file (these are from converting the List so as to print the outputs into the file).
Once this is done, the subgraphs part can be run. 

Our graph (the data object representing all the cloud elements and their connectivity through out the start and end times):
* Sparse, disconnected and directed. 
* There are no cycles

Our initial approach to determine all the connected subgraphs within this graph is:
* Partition nodes such that possible connected nodes are together
* On each partition: eliminate only subgraphs that are found in that partition 
* Merge consecutive partitions and repeat subgraph elimination
* Continue until one partition remains OR all nodes are gone

Our approach ensures a maximum number of iterations of log(paritions)/log(2) + 1

Outstanding TODOs:
* continued testing
* allowing to read the edgelist directly from the RDD (ie. eliminate the text writing part)

import xmltodict, json, functools, sys
import networkx as nx
from pprint import pprint
import graphviz as gv

def add_nodes(graph, nodes):
    for n in nodes:
        if isinstance(n, tuple):
            graph.node(n[0], **n[1])
        else:
            graph.node(n) #_attributes={"style":"filled", "fillcolor":"white", "tooltip": "brightness field"}
    return graph


def add_edges(graph, edges):
    for e in edges:
        if isinstance(e[0], tuple):
            graph.edge(*e[0], **e[1])
        else:
            graph.edge(*e)
    return graph


def main(argFile, maxLimit, edgeList):
    inF = open(edgeList, 'r')
    tuples = eval(inF.readline())
    inF.close()

    G = nx.DiGraph(tuples)
    weakConnComponents = []
    for w in nx.weakly_connected_component_subgraphs(G):
        weakConnComponents.append(w.edges())

    weakConnComponents.sort(key=lambda x: len(x), reverse=True)

    #traverse weak component
    """
    for w in nx.weakly_connected_component_subgraphs(G):
    sorted(nx.weakly_connected_component_subgraphs(G), key=len, reverse = True)]
    """

    # iterate through all weakConnComponents here, lay them out one on top of another
    yPos = 0
    for i in range(0, int(maxLimit)): #len(weakConnComponents)

        digraph = functools.partial(gv.Digraph, graph_attr={"rankdir": "LR", }, format='svg') #"ordering":"out"
        nodes = set()
        for edgeTup in weakConnComponents[i]:
            nodes.add(edgeTup[0])
            nodes.add(edgeTup[1])
        nodes = list(nodes)
        edges = weakConnComponents[i]


        add_edges(add_nodes(digraph(), nodes), edges).render('/data/cluster-local/notebook_data/img/g' + str(i))


        with open('/data/cluster-local/notebook_data/img/g{0}.svg'.format(i)) as fd:
            doc = xmltodict.parse(fd.read())

            nodeYLocation = {}
            for elem in doc["svg"]["g"]["g"]:
                if elem["@class"] == "node":
                    #(Cx, Cy) x, y coordinates of center, origin top left corner
                    #(Rx, Ry) radius of ellipse along x, y axes
                    nodeYLocation[elem["title"]] = int(elem["ellipse"]["@cy"])

            #minNode = max(nodeYLocation, key=nodeYLocation.get)

            for key in nodeYLocation:

            yPos += nodeYLocation[max(nodeYLocation, key=nodeYLocation.get)]
